Global Mirror with Change Volumes

Firewall Considerations

FlashSystem replication uses a combination of the management IP address along with dedicated replication IP addresses to communicate with the target cluster.  Consequently, the management subnet (these are the cluster IP addresses that are used to log into the GUI) must be allowed to communicate with each other across sites AND the data subnet(s) must be allowed to communicate with each other across sites.  Replicated data will only traverse the data subnets, so bandwidth is not a concern for the management ports.

Assign IP Addresses

On the source cluster, log into the GUI.

From the side menu, click on Settings â†’ Network

Click on Ethernet Ports

Click on the row for the desired port (ideally, a 10Gbps port) from Node 1 and then click on the Actions pull-down.

Select Modify IP Settings

Enter the appropriate IP address, subnet mask, and gateway and then click Modify

Repeat the previous 3 steps for the same port on the other node as well as any other ports that are to be used for replication. 

Assign Ethernet Ports to Copy Groups

While in the Ethernet panel from the previous procedure, select the first replication port that was assigned an IP and click on the actions pull-down

Select Modify Remote Copy

Set IPv4 remote copy to Group 1 and click Modify

Repeat the previous 3 steps for the same port on node 2 and also set that port to Group 1

If you are using four ports on each cluster, you can set the second port on each node to Group 2 to allow for parallel traffic.  Notice in the picture below that there is a port from each node in each of the copy groups

Create a Partnership

On the source cluster GUI, click on the side menu and select Copy Services Ã  Partnerships

Click on Create Partnership

In the Create Partnership window, set the Type to IP. 

Enter the partner systemâ€™s management (GUI) IP address in the field for Partner system IP address. 

Set the link bandwidth to the value for the size of the WAN link between sites (you can throttle the connectivity here if you donâ€™t wish to use the entire link bandwidth).  This value is in megabits (Mb) per second. 

Set the desired Background copy rate percentage.      This is the percent of bandwidth that can be used for background copy operations.  If the links are not being used for iSCSI host connections, start by setting this value to 80%.  (Can increase or decrease later if needed).

Check the Compression enabled box.

Click  OK

The partnership will be created and be in a state of Partially Configured

Repeat these steps on the partner cluster

Create Change Volumes

This procedure is written specifically to use Global Mirror with Change Volumes.  As a best practice, we recommend creating the change volumes up from vs creating them automatically when defining the relationship.

In the GUI for the Source Cluster:

On the side menu, select Volumes Ã  Volumes

 

Determine the volume(s) that will be replicated and make note of the sizes.

Click on Create Volumes

On the Create Volumes window:

Set the Pool to the SAME pool as the source volumes identified in the previous step.

Create the quantity, capacity, and size of volumes to match source volumes.

Set the name to match the source volumes + _CV (or some other notation to identify these as change volumes)

Set the Capacity savings to Thin-provisioned

Use the Define another volume to add additional volumes with different capacities.

Leave I/O group at Automatic

Click Create

Create Volume(s) on the Target Cluster

In order to create a remote copy relationship to another system, you must first create volumes on that cluster that are equal in size to the volumes that will be replicated from the source cluster.

Follow the steps in the Create Volumes procedure to create volumes on the target cluster. 

Create Change Volume(s) on the Target Cluster

In the GUI for the Target Cluster:

On the side menu, select Volumes Ã  Volumes

Click on Create Volumes

On the Create Volumes window:

Set the Pool to the SAME pool as the target volumes created in the previous step.

Create the quantity, capacity, and size of volumes to match source volumes.

Set the name to match the source volumes + _DRCV (or some other notation to identify these as remote site change volumes)

Set the Capacity savings to Thin-provisioned

Use the Define another volume to add additional volumes with different capacities.

Leave I/O group at Automatic

Click Create

Create Empty Consistency Group

If the volumes that are being replicated have a relationship to one another (such as members of the same SYSBAS or IASP, members of a volume group, volumes for a database, log volumes, etc) then they need to reside inside a consistency group.

In the GUI for the Source Cluster:

On the side menu, select Copy  Services Ã  Remote Copy

Click on Create Consistency Group

Enter a name for the consistency group and then click Next

Select On another system and choose the target cluster from the pull-down and then click Next

Select No, create an empty consistency group and then click Finish to create the empty consistency group

This is how the empty consistency group will appear

Create Remote Copy Relationships

In the GUI for the Source Cluster:

On the side menu, select Copy  Services â†’ Remote Copy

Select the row that says Not in a Group and then click on the Actions pull-down and choose Create Relationship

On the Create Relationship panel choose Global Mirror with Change Volumes and click Next (Note, the Add Consistency Protection option does not pertain to Global Mirror with Change Volumes so it doesnâ€™t matter if that is check or not checked)

Select On another system, choose the target cluster from the pull-down, and then click Next

Choose the first volume to be replicated on the source cluster from the Master pull-down.  Verify the size shown is correct, a list of candidate volumes on the target cluster that are equal in size will be shown in Auxiliary pull-down.  Choose the appropriate target volume and click Add

Select Yes, add a master change volume and click Next

Select Use existing volume for the master change volume and select the appropriate change volume from the pull-down (hint, this volume is one that was create in the Create Change Volume(s) on the Source Cluster section of this document).  If the desired change volume is not shown in the pull-down, double check the size to ensure it matches the source volume

Set the Cycling Mode to Multiple and Cycle Period to 300 seconds.  This will set the frequency at which the changes are flashed to the change volume. Decreasing the cycle period improves RPO, so it is suggested to keep that number as low as possible if this were a DR configuration. For data migrations, leaving the default of 300 is recommended.

Repeat the previous 4 steps to add all desired volumes and then click Next

Select No, the volumes are not synchronized and then click Next

Select No, do not start copying and then click Finish

The relationships will be created and will be shown in an Inconsistent Stopped State

In order to view the change volumes and cycle period in the table, right-click on the table header and click the boxes next to Master Change Volume, Auxiliary Change Volume, and Cycle Period

You can now see that these relationships have master change volumes assigned, but they do not have Auxiliary Change Volumes defined.  Proceed to the next section to add change volumes on the Target (Auxiliary) Cluster.

Define Change Volumes

In the GUI for the Target Cluster:

On the side menu, select Copy  Services â†’ Remote Copy

Click the arrow next to Not in a Group to expand that section and view the newly created relationships.

In order to view the change volumes and cycle period in the table, right-click on the table header and click the boxes next to Master Change Volume, Auxiliary Change Volume, and Cycle Period

Add a change volume to a relationship by clicking on the row for that relationship, click the Actions pull-down and select Change Volumes Ã  Add Existing

Select the appropriate change volume from the pull-down and then click Add (if the desired change volume is not shown, verify that the volume was created as the same size as the target volume).

Set the Cycling Mode to Multiple and the Cycle Period to 300 seconds to match the settings on the Master change volume and then click OK

The Auxiliary Change Volume will now be shown in the table.

Repeat the previous 4 steps to add Auxiliary Change Volumes to all relationships

Start Remote Copy Relationships

In the GUI for the Source Cluster:

On the side menu, select Copy  Services â†’ Remote Copy

If not already done, expand the Not in a group section to view the relationships

Click on the row of the relationship that will be started, click the Actions pull-down and select Start

The relationship will start copying data from the Source Cluster to the Target Cluster.  The state of the relationship will now show Inconsistent Copying

You can view the status of the remote copy operation by clicking on the clipboard in the upper-right of the GUI.  You will see Remote-Copy Operation in the Running Tasks section.  Click View

The sync progress will be shown.  Once the progress bar reaches 100%, the initial sync is complete and the relationship can be added to the consistency group in the next section.

Start additional relationships as desired. When trying to determine how many relationships to start at once, keep in mind that while the initial sync is occurring, the actual space consumed by the change volume can grow significantly, so be sure that the pools have enough free space to support the change volumes growing to full size.

Add Remote Copy to Consistency Group

When using change volumes, you must first stop the remote copy relationship and the consistency group before adding to a consistency group. Use the following steps to add remote copy relationships to a consistency group.

From the side menu, select Copy Service â†’ Remote Copy

Click on Not in a Group to view all of the remote copy relationships that are not currently part of a consistency group

Select the relationship to add (or ctrl-click to add multiple), right click and select Stop

Verify the relationships shown are correct and then click Stop Relationships

If the consistency group is not empty, right click on the consistency group and select Stop

Click on Stop Consistency Group

Right click the selected relationships again and select Add to Consistency Group

Choose the desired consistency group from the pull-down and click Add to Consistency Group

Once the relationship are added, right click on the consistency group and select Start

Click Start Consistency Group
